This paper discusses the use of cryptographic techniques in outsourced database systems to ensure data privacy, which falls under the category of database systems (cs.DB). The paper also discusses the need to balance efficiency and privacy, which is a common concern in the field of computer security (cs.CR). The use of differentially private sanitizers and oblivious RAM also suggests a focus on data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the need to hide the memory access pattern from the server, which is a common concern in the field of cybersecurity (cs.CY). Finally, the paper presents a generic construction of differentially private outsourced databases, which involves machine learning techniques such as differential privacy (cs.LG).
